00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:15.150
are doing.

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:18.100
I mean, animation
is a huge topic.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:22.380
I'm not going to talk about
techniques or theory or any

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:25.070
of that kind of stuff.

00:03:25.070 --> 00:03:30.760
But I do want to talk about
when it's a good idea to use it

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:33.280
maybe in your own work.

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.600
And there may be more
reasons why it might be good.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:40.050
But these are the ones that
I came up with for today.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:47.900
So animation is good when
synthesizing, reinforcing,

00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:51.400
or recapping information
in a simple, visual way.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:53.720
Cows plus farts
equals global warming.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:04:00.050
So taking abstract ideas
or summarizing information

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:02.210
and presenting it very
simply is something

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:04.910
that animation is
really good at.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:08.120
So when thinking about
developing your own scripts,

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:13.520
you can think about moments
where the visual story could

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:17.200
be augmented with some sort
of encapsulation or summary

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:22.820
that is worthy of animation.

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:24.940
And here's one that's
pretty obvious.

00:04:24.940 --> 00:04:28.820
The subject cannot be seen,
it's microscopic, cosmic,

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:31.140
or theoretical and abstract.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:36.562
So those are often good times
to think about animation.

00:04:36.562 --> 00:04:38.770
And we have some examples
of where this sort of thing

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:42.070
is employed later.

00:04:42.070 --> 00:04:44.079
John came up with this one.

00:04:44.079 --> 00:04:45.620
Actually, John helped
with all these.

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:47.990
Because I was really
busy this week.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:49.850
So I really appreciate it.

00:04:49.850 --> 00:04:51.305
Footage is not
easily attainable.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:58.300
So say you want to do a video
about-- well, in your case,

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:01.720
you know you're doing
navel engineering.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:04.340
Maybe you want to shoot
something about, like,

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:05.760
the bottom of the ship.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:10.240
Or something,
you're going to have

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:12.510
to hire a team of scuba
divers to get down there

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:14.690
and shoot the hull of the ship.

00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:21.450
So that might be a nice
opportunity for visualization

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:25.280
that can't be attained
through live action.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:27.480
And kind of the
catch-all category

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:30.990
is that animation adds
visual engagement.

00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:34.860
The story is somehow
made better by using it.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:38.440
And that's sort of an abstract,
subjective thing to say.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:40.150
But I think the best
way to demonstrate

00:05:40.150 --> 00:05:41.460
that is just to show examples.

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:47.000
Which I'll do in a bit.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.980
So animation is sort of
silly or not a great choice--

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:54.040
we use this term a lot.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.000
Like, is this eye
candy, or is this really

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.875
a functional part of the story?

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:09.220
Again, is it eye candy or
is the story made better?

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:13.420
So just using animation
because it's cool or it's neat

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:17.500
can actually distance the
viewer and disengage them

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:19.010
from the experience.

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:21.370
Because, I don't know if
you guys watch-- you know,

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:23.580
you've seen a movie
like Transformers.

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:27.780
Or, god, what are some of
these ridiculously visually

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:30.010
opulent movies, you know?

00:06:30.010 --> 00:06:33.620
And a lot of times when I
watch those sorts of things,

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:37.130
I begin to emotionally
disengaged from them.

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:38.930
Because all I'm doing
is being bombarded

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:40.120
by visual information.

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:44.362
There's no story that's really
compelling or engaging me.

00:06:44.362 --> 00:06:45.820
So that's something
to think about.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:51.750
Live action is really great
that at a number of things.

00:06:51.750 --> 00:06:53.750
And these are some of the
things I came up with.

00:06:56.370 --> 00:06:59.470
The notion of personality,
the human face,

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:01.360
the human experience.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:06.670
The host, is Elizabeth
talked about on Monday.

00:07:06.670 --> 00:07:11.880
Location, creating--
animation can create

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:14.860
a lot of interesting locations.

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:19.870
But why would you
draw the MIT campus

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:25.110
when you have it right in
front of you, for instance?

00:07:25.110 --> 00:07:29.390
And again, the notion
of human interaction.

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:35.640
Humans talking to each other
and engaging with each other

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:40.550
is something that live
action is really good at.

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.230
And the final,
catch-all category

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:44.500
is you just can't think
of anything better to do.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:46.677
So, oh, I'm just going
to animate that part.

00:07:46.677 --> 00:07:48.260
I don't really want
to think about how

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:49.800
I'm going to present this.

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:53.720
So I'm just going to
do some animation.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:55.240
And that's not the best choice.

00:07:55.240 --> 00:07:57.560
You should be
making choices based

00:07:57.560 --> 00:07:59.300
on what the strengths
of animation are

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:02.452
and the strength of live action.

00:08:02.452 --> 00:08:03.910
PROFESSOR: And just
to add to that,

00:08:03.910 --> 00:08:05.970
that's also the
easiest choice to make.

00:08:05.970 --> 00:08:07.907
And the one that
happens most often.

00:08:07.907 --> 00:08:09.365
Or the one that
happened most often

00:08:09.365 --> 00:08:12.140
when we were making seasons
one and two is that we'd

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:14.310
hit a point in the script
that looks a little bit

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:17.227
complex in terms of
visual execution.

00:08:17.227 --> 00:08:19.310
And we'd say, well, what
are you going to do here?

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:22.770
And the host or the cast
would say, oh, well,

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:25.177
we're just going to animate it.

00:08:25.177 --> 00:08:27.510
As if, like, that was going
to solve all their problems.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:32.559
And I think that
these points may sound

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:34.520
pretty reasonable and obvious.

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:38.789
But it's very, very hard to
thoughtfully integrate that

00:08:38.789 --> 00:08:40.169
into your visual script.

00:08:40.169 --> 00:08:43.000
So I really encourage you
guys to think about especially

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.330
the third point, not
defaulting to animation

00:08:45.330 --> 00:08:49.520
because you don't want to figure
out how to visually integrate

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:51.400
your script into the video.

